# Engineering Rules

## Startup Tools
- Required quality tools are **pinned**, not floating. Install each tool at the
  exact ref recorded below; never resolve "latest". Bumping a pin is a human
  commit, not an agent action.
- Language tool table:
  - TypeScript: mutation `stryker-mutator` (StrykerJS, version pinned in
    package.json); DRY `jscpd` (pinned in package.json); CRAP computed as
    coverage x cyclomatic complexity from the coverage reporter + complexity
    scripts in `scripts/quality/`.
  - Babashka/Clojure (swarm scripts): mutation `github.com/unclebob/clj-mutate`,
    CRAP `github.com/unclebob/crap4clj`, DRY `github.com/unclebob/dry4clj` — each
    at the SHA recorded in `swarmforge.lock.json`.
- APS tools (`gherkin-parser`, `gherkin-mutator`, IR-DRY checker) come from
  `github.com/unclebob/Acceptance-Pipeline-Specification` pinned at
  `accaa33d503340c56513ef387258f8da929ba902`. Prefer the Babashka APS tools;
  use the Go tools only if the Babashka ones fail in this environment. Do not
  reimplement APS commands in the project.

## Design And Testability
- Work in small, reviewable increments.
- Prefer the simplest design that supports the current behavior and leaves clear
  options for the next step.
- Keep tests close to the behavior being changed.
- Separate testable modules from environmentally unsuitable modules. In this
  project the unsuitable boundary is: the VS Code Extension API surface, the
  webview execution context, and live tmux/PTY interaction. Everything else —
  socket discovery, `.swarmforge/` state parsing, handoff protocol, grid layout
  logic, backlog parsing — must be a testable module reachable without booting
  VS Code.
- Only testable modules participate in tools that run tests: unit tests,
  acceptance tests, coverage, mutation testing, CRAP analysis, DRY analysis that
  invokes tests, and property tests.
- Keep property tests separate from normal verification. Do not include
  property-test tags in normal unit coverage, Gherkin acceptance mutation,
  language mutation, CRAP, or coverage commands unless the role owns
  property-test verification or the user explicitly asks.

## Acceptance Pipeline
- Use github.com/unclebob/Acceptance-Pipeline-Specification (pinned, see above)
  for Gherkin acceptance tests.
- Feature files live in `specs/features/`, separated by behavior and technology.
  Backlog items reference their feature files; the feature files are the durable
  acceptance contract and outlive the backlog item.
- Project-specific acceptance components live in `specs/pipeline/`: the
  acceptance entrypoint generator, acceptance runtime, project step handlers,
  runner adapter, and convenience scripts. Step handlers drive the testable
  host-side core through its CLI/module surface, never through the VS Code UI.
- Gherkin acceptance mutation means running `gherkin-mutator` to mutate Gherkin
  example values in the JSON IR. It is distinct from language mutation of source.
- Gherkin acceptance mutation runs must report periodic progress/status so agents
  can distinguish normal long-running work from a hang.

## Verification
- Before running language, build, or test commands, prefer project-local
  cache/configuration paths inside the assigned worktree.
- Run acceptance generation and acceptance tests sequentially. Avoid running
  whole-suite test commands concurrently with acceptance generation.
- Run the relevant local verification command before handoff whenever the
  project has one.

## Diagrams
- The project's documentation must include an up-to-date architecture
  diagram, plus any other diagram relevant to understanding the system (the
  project-specific engineering article names which). The documenter owns
  keeping them current: whenever a parcel changes what a diagram depicts,
  the diagram is updated in that documentation pass.
- Diagrams live under `docs/` in a text-based source format (e.g. Mermaid)
  so changes diff, review, and merge like code; no binary-only diagram
  sources.

## Guardrails
- Do not edit mutation testing or Gherkin acceptance mutation manifests by hand;
  approved mutation tools update those manifests in their normal runs.
- Do not commit unrelated local changes or generated artifacts unless required
  for the task.
- Before relying on an unfamiliar command, inspect local help or project
  documentation.
- Mutation-testing caches and incremental-run manifests (e.g. StrykerJS's
  incremental cache file) are local state, not source: gitignore them,
  never commit them. A tracked mutation cache is exactly how BL-105's
  113 MB blob entered history and made a branch unpushable — the tool
  reads/writes it locally regardless of whether git tracks it.
